Setbacks are part of every athlete’s journey. Filipino pole vaulter EJ Obiena, a Southeast Asian Games&nbsp; record holder, faced his own at the 2024 Paris Olympics. Though he narrowly missed the bronze, his&nbsp; determination remains an inspiration. While this could have been a defining moment in his career for&nbsp; many, Obiena saw it as a chance to show his indomitable spirit. His story of perseverance endeared him&nbsp; even more to his fellow Filipinos.&nbsp;
Obiena sets his sights for greater achievements. When asked about his plans leading up to the 2028&nbsp; Olympics in Los Angeles, he admits that it’s difficult to provide a concrete answer. However, he eagerly&nbsp; anticipates the future, stating, “
I’m planning for next year, I need to decide where I’m going to be training.&nbsp; Where are the training camps? We have both indoor and outdoor world championship in Asia, which is in&nbsp; China and Japan. So therefore, I’m looking around, but I know that I have a place here, Vermosa, and&nbsp; soon it’s going to be perfect. There’s a few more in the works, but as of now, it’s already looking like this is&nbsp; where I want to be training at.”
Obiena shared.&nbsp;
EJ Obiena, brand ambassador for Vermosa, trains at the Ayala Vermosa Sports Hub (AVSH) when in the&nbsp; Philippines. As he looks towards the future, Obiena’s vision reaches beyond personal success—he’s&nbsp; committed to growing and elevating the pole-vaulting sport for the nation. He is driven by a desire to&nbsp; inspire the next generation of athletes. And at the heart of this ambition lies Vermosa. This Ayala Land&nbsp; estate in Imus, Cavite, with its world-class facilities and commitment to sports development, facilitates an&nbsp; opportunity for the Philippines to establish itself as a force to be reckoned with in the world of pole&nbsp; vaulting and other sports. It also enables the potential for sports excellence of kids from the grassroots.&nbsp;&nbsp;
Beyond the physical infrastructure, Vermosa also offers comprehensive sports development programs&nbsp; that focus on coaching, sports science, and athlete well-being. Obiena envisions these programs as the&nbsp; driving force behind the Philippines’ rise in pole vaulting, providing aspiring athletes with the guidance,&nbsp; resources, and support they need to reach their full potential.&nbsp;&nbsp;
Obiena expressed his commitment to empowering the youth and imparting his knowledge of sports. The&nbsp; Philippines is currently experiencing a surge of interest in the Olympics, marking a golden age for sports.&nbsp;
“I think we should capitalize on that inspiration of kids, ‘I want to try this sport. I want to try weightlifting,&nbsp; gymnastics, and pole vault.’ And with that, Ayala Land and Vermosa definitely, definitely stepped up.&nbsp; Therefore, we’re planning a few clinics to make sure that these kids hopefully are going to be the next&nbsp; champions. We have a facility; we have housing for them. It’s a perfect ecosystem for high performance&nbsp; events and high-performance athletic prowess,”
he said.&nbsp;
Obiena also recognizes the importance of raising the stature of pole vaulting in the Philippines. Through&nbsp; his own success on the international stage and the success of the athletes he helps nurture, he aims to&nbsp; inspire a newfound appreciation for the sport among the Filipino public. This, in turn, will drive greater&nbsp; investment, support, and participation in pole vaulting at all levels.&nbsp;
Vermosa’s state-of-the-art training facilities provide athletes and sports enthusiasts with the tools they&nbsp; need to hone their skills and push the boundaries of their performance. Obiena also finds the&nbsp; convenience of having everything he needs within the estate helps him maintain focus,
“Vermosa is a&nbsp; perfect camp, perfect place to actually grow and train and really focus. Athletes who want to focus and&nbsp; really dive deep into it can do training camps there. I wake up, I don’t need to drive. I walk to the track.&nbsp;
After I train, I have my food there, I have my place to rest. I have my physios, I have the gym, I have the&nbsp; pool. All of these things would lead you into obsessing and being able to fully utilize your time into your&nbsp; sport. And that’s what Vermosa really provides. And more than just that, the high level of facility that they&nbsp; provide is a plus,
” Obiena said.&nbsp;
With Vermosa as the center of this plan, Obiena’s dreams for the future of Philippine pole vaulting are well&nbsp; within reach. He envisions the development of dedicated training facilities and clinics in Vermosa that will&nbsp; cater specifically to pole vaulting, providing invaluable support and guidance to young athletes.&nbsp;&nbsp;
Obiena believes that Vermosa is the perfect destination for both athletes and individuals who love staying&nbsp; active.
“Because of first the facility, it’s a plus for us because we get to do all of it, but for everyone who’s&nbsp; doing swimming, they have the pool there. It’s a very good pool. You have the gym, it’s high quality. And&nbsp; of course, the track. And with the track, I know how it was set up and how it was more or less planned. It’s&nbsp; a perfect place for me.”
Obiena shared.&nbsp;
Vermosa’s commitment to creating a vibrant community of athletes, coaches, and enthusiasts is a key&nbsp; aspect of its sports development vision. By bringing together like-minded individuals who share a passion&nbsp; for sports, Vermosa aims to cultivate an environment that is both supportive and inspiring, further fueling&nbsp; the growth and development of the sport in the Philippines.&nbsp;&nbsp;
ADVT.
